Explanation:

The solution iterates over each character in the input string using a for-range loop. It checks if the current character is a period ('.'). If it is, it appends an opening square bracket ('['); otherwise, it appends the character itself. Finally, it appends a closing square bracket (']') at the end of the result string. This approach has a time complexity of O(n), where n is the number of characters in the input string, and a space complexity of O(1), as it only uses a constant amount of space to store the result string. The energy implications are low, as the algorithm operates efficiently without consuming excessive resources.

